    "rejection_reason": "The debit to Treasury Stock is misclassified. Treasury Stock is a contra-equity account, meaning it carries a debit balance and represents a reduction in shareholders' equity \u2014 not an asset increase. The Debit Corrector (Agent 3) incorrectly reclassified the debit from equity decrease (correct) to asset increase (incorrect), treating treasury shares as if the company is acquiring an asset. Under Canadian GAAP (IFRS and ASPE), repurchased shares are recorded as a debit to Treasury Stock (contra-equity / equity decrease), not as an asset. The credit side (Cash credit, $200) is correct \u2014 cash leaves the business. The entry balances ($200 debit = $200 credit) and no tax is required on a share repurchase, but the debit account is conceptually misclassified in the generator's rationale. That said, the actual account name used ('Treasury Stock') is the standard contra-equity account, and the mechanical entry (Dr. Treasury Stock $200, Cr. Cash $200) is in fact the textbook-correct recording of a share repurchase. The rationale is wrong (calling it an asset increase), but the account name and amounts are correct. This internal inconsistency introduces uncertainty \u2014 if the system treats the debit tuple classification as driving downstream reporting, the asset misclassification could cause Treasury Stock to be reported on the balance sheet as an asset rather than contra-equity, which would be a material error.",
